EG.CFT.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Access to clean fuels and technologies for cooking is the proportion of total population primarily using clean cooking fuels and technologies for cooking. Under WHO guidelines, kerosene is excluded from clean cooking fuels.
EG.CFT.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Access to clean fuels and technologies for cooking
EG.CFT.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.source: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from WHO Global Household Energy database.
EG.CFT.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.dataset: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from WHO Global Household Energy database.

EG.EGY.PRIM.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.def: Energy intensity level of primary energy is the ratio between energy supply and gross domestic product measured at purchasing power parity. Energy intensity is an indication of how much energy is used to produce one unit of economic output. Lower ratio indicates that less energy is used to produce one unit of output.
EG.EGY.PRIM.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.name: Energy intensity level of primary energy
EG.EGY.PRIM.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.source: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from the SE4ALL Global Tracking Framework led jointly by the World Bank, International Energy Agency, and the Energy Sector Management Assistance Program.
EG.EGY.PRIM.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.dataset: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from the SE4ALL Global Tracking Framework led jointly by the World Bank, International Energy Agency, and the Energy Sector Management Assistance Program.

EG.ELC.ACCS.RU.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Access to electricity, rural is the percentage of rural population with access to electricity.
EG.ELC.ACCS.RU.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Access to electricity
EG.ELC.ACCS.RU.ZS-energyProductionUse.source: World Bank Global Electrification Database from "Tracking SDG 7: The Energy Progress Report" led jointly by the custodian agencies: the International Energy Agency (IEA), the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD), the World Bank and the World Health Organization (WHO).
EG.ELC.ACCS.RU.ZS-energyProductionUse.dataset: World Bank Global Electrification Database from "Tracking SDG 7: The Energy Progress Report" led jointly by the custodian agencies: the International Energy Agency (IEA), the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD), the World Bank and the World Health Organization (WHO).

EG.ELC.ACCS.UR.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Access to electricity, urban is the percentage of urban population with access to electricity.
EG.ELC.ACCS.UR.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Access to electricity
EG.ELC.ACCS.UR.ZS-energyProductionUse.source: World Bank Global Electrification Database from "Tracking SDG 7: The Energy Progress Report" led jointly by the custodian agencies: the International Energy Agency (IEA), the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD), the World Bank and the World Health Organization (WHO).
EG.ELC.ACCS.UR.ZS-energyProductionUse.dataset: World Bank Global Electrification Database from "Tracking SDG 7: The Energy Progress Report" led jointly by the custodian agencies: the International Energy Agency (IEA), the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD), the World Bank and the World Health Organization (WHO).

EG.ELC.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Access to electricity is the percentage of population with access to electricity. Electrification data are collected from industry, national surveys and international sources.
EG.ELC.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Access to electricity
EG.ELC.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.source: World Bank Global Electrification Database from "Tracking SDG 7: The Energy Progress Report" led jointly by the custodian agencies: the International Energy Agency (IEA), the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD), the World Bank and the World Health Organization (WHO).
EG.ELC.ACCS.ZS-energyProductionUse.dataset: World Bank Global Electrification Database from "Tracking SDG 7: The Energy Progress Report" led jointly by the custodian agencies: the International Energy Agency (IEA), the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD), the World Bank and the World Health Organization (WHO).

EG.ELC.COAL.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Sources of electricity refer to the inputs used to generate electricity. Coal refers to all coal and brown coal, both primary (including hard coal and lignite-brown coal) and derived fuels (including patent fuel, coke oven coke, gas coke, coke oven gas, and blast furnace gas). Peat is also included in this category.
EG.ELC.COAL.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from coal sources

EG.ELC.FOSL.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Sources of electricity refer to the inputs used to generate electricity. Oil refers to crude oil and petroleum products. Gas refers to natural gas but excludes natural gas liquids. Coal refers to all coal and brown coal, both primary (including hard coal and lignite-brown coal) and derived fuels (including patent fuel, coke oven coke, gas coke, coke oven gas, and blast furnace gas). Peat is also included in this category.
EG.ELC.FOSL.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from oil, gas and coal sources

EG.ELC.HYRO.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Sources of electricity refer to the inputs used to generate electricity. Hydropower refers to electricity produced by hydroelectric power plants.
EG.ELC.HYRO.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from hydroelectric sources

EG.ELC.LOSS.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Electric power transmission and distribution losses include losses in transmission between sources of supply and points of distribution and in the distribution to consumers, including pilferage.
EG.ELC.LOSS.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electric power transmission and distribution losses

EG.ELC.NGAS.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Sources of electricity refer to the inputs used to generate electricity. Gas refers to natural gas but excludes natural gas liquids.
EG.ELC.NGAS.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from natural gas sources

EG.ELC.NUCL.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Sources of electricity refer to the inputs used to generate electricity. Nuclear power refers to electricity produced by nuclear power plants.
EG.ELC.NUCL.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from nuclear sources

EG.ELC.PETR.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Sources of electricity refer to the inputs used to generate electricity. Oil refers to crude oil and petroleum products.
EG.ELC.PETR.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from oil sources

EG.ELC.RNEW.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Renewable electricity is the share of electrity generated by renewable power plants in total electricity generated by all types of plants.
EG.ELC.RNEW.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Renewable electricity output

EG.ELC.RNWX.KH-energyProductionUse.def: Electricity production from renewable sources, excluding hydroelectric, includes geothermal, solar, tides, wind, biomass, and biofuels.
EG.ELC.RNWX.KH-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from renewable sources

EG.ELC.RNWX.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Electricity production from renewable sources, excluding hydroelectric, includes geothermal, solar, tides, wind, biomass, and biofuels.
EG.ELC.RNWX.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Electricity production from renewable sources

EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Renewable energy consumption is the share of renewables energy in total final energy consumption.
EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Renewable energy consumption
EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-energyProductionUse.source: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from the SE4ALL Global Tracking Framework led jointly by the World Bank, International Energy Agency, and the Energy Sector Management Assistance Program.
EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-energyProductionUse.dataset: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from the SE4ALL Global Tracking Framework led jointly by the World Bank, International Energy Agency, and the Energy Sector Management Assistance Program.

EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP-energyProductionUse.def: GDP per unit of energy use is the PPP GDP per kilogram of oil equivalent of energy use. PPP GDP is gross domestic product converted to current international dollars using purchasing power parity rates based on the 2017 ICP round. An international dollar has the same purchasing power over GDP as a U.S. dollar has in the United States.
EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP-energyProductionUse.name: GDP per unit of energy use
EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP-energyProductionUse.dim: PPP $ per kg of oil equivalent
EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP-energyProductionUse.units: PPP $ per kg of oil equivalent

EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.def: GDP per unit of energy use is the PPP GDP per kilogram of oil equivalent of energy use. PPP GDP is gross domestic product converted to 2017 constant international dollars using purchasing power parity rates. An international dollar has the same purchasing power over GDP as a U.S. dollar has in the United States.
EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.name: GDP per unit of energy use
EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.dim: constant 2017 PPP $ per kg of oil equivalent
EG.GDP.PUSE.KO.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.units: constant 2017 PPP $ per kg of oil equivalent

EG.IMP.CONS.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Net energy imports are estimated as energy use less production, both measured in oil equivalents. A negative value indicates that the country is a net exporter. Energy use refers to use of primary energy before transformation to other end-use fuels, which is equal to indigenous production plus imports and stock changes, minus exports and fuels supplied to ships and aircraft engaged in international transport.
EG.IMP.CONS.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Energy imports, net

EG.USE.COMM.CL.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Clean energy is noncarbohydrate energy that does not produce carbon dioxide when generated. It includes hydropower and nuclear, geothermal, and solar power, among others.
EG.USE.COMM.CL.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Alternative and nuclear energy

EG.USE.COMM.FO.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Fossil fuel comprises coal, oil, petroleum, and natural gas products.
EG.USE.COMM.FO.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Fossil fuel energy consumption

EG.USE.COMM.GD.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.def: Energy use per PPP GDP is the kilogram of oil equivalent of energy use per constant PPP GDP. Energy use refers to use of primary energy before transformation to other end-use fuels, which is equal to indigenous production plus imports and stock changes, minus exports and fuels supplied to ships and aircraft engaged in international transport. PPP GDP is gross domestic product converted to 2017 constant international dollars using purchasing power parity rates. An international dollar has the same purchasing power over GDP as a U.S. dollar has in the United States.
EG.USE.COMM.GD.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.name: Energy use
EG.USE.COMM.GD.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.dim: kg of oil equivalent) per $1,000 GDP (constant 2017 PPP
EG.USE.COMM.GD.PP.KD-energyProductionUse.units: kg of oil equivalent) per $1,000 GDP (constant 2017 PPP

EG.USE.CRNW.ZS-energyProductionUse.def: Combustible renewables and waste comprise solid biomass, liquid biomass, biogas, industrial waste, and municipal waste, measured as a percentage of total energy use.
EG.USE.CRNW.ZS-energyProductionUse.name: Combustible renewables and waste

EG.USE.ELEC.KH.PC-energyProductionUse.def: Electric power consumption measures the production of power plants and combined heat and power plants less transmission, distribution, and transformation losses and own use by heat and power plants.
EG.USE.ELEC.KH.PC-energyProductionUse.name: Electric power consumption

EG.USE.PCAP.KG.OE-energyProductionUse.def: Energy use refers to use of primary energy before transformation to other end-use fuels, which is equal to indigenous production plus imports and stock changes, minus exports and fuels supplied to ships and aircraft engaged in international transport.
EG.USE.PCAP.KG.OE-energyProductionUse.name: Energy use
EG.USE.PCAP.KG.OE-energyProductionUse.dim: kg of oil equivalent per capita
EG.USE.PCAP.KG.OE-energyProductionUse.units: kg of oil equivalent per capita
